🎪202208181056 Quest Society:Archive1: 🎓202409271001 
🎲🥞🍎 📌 ⭐ 🔔 🕰️ [13]
Essence25EHP78E🚀Enabling Autonomy
ID: [25EHP78E] 🥚
+Essence+Tags: Essence
🧭
Ivy: Quest Society is a framework that fundamentally allows people to self-organize in social-political sub societies they want for themselves. Ivy: Allowing people what "they want" implies doing so without harming what others want for themselves.
[🌱 Gaia Share]↴
:CornerRibbon:
🧭
Ivy: Gaia Share is an ethical accounting of resources to allow fundamental autonomy. Ivy: If you want a city that only allows cat lovers, you are free to start one with your Gaia shares, and let cat-lovers join with their Gaia shares for a continuous cat-lovers zone. Ivy: What you can't do, is to prevent cat lovers from leaving and withdrawing their shares as they leave. Ivy: If the city fails to get enough Gaia shares for its size, the city must yield extra territories so people who left could start their own zone. Ivy: If a society you know does not do this, it is violating an ethical principle, just like a bank not allowing its clients to withdraw, and failing to show a balance of how much a client has deposited or inherited. Ivy: Quest Society does not fail this principle. You can withdraw. It is normal. It is a choice. Ivy: If someone suggests that it is dangerous to let people withdraw, you could respond by asking "then why is it okay for people to withdraw from banks normally? Aren't there fairer ways to tell if someone is a terrorist than whether they are trying to withdraw? If you just don't let them withdraw, they you are unethically detaining them. Then you are the terrorist."
[🪙 Priority Currency]↴
:CornerRibbon:
🧭
Ivy: Priority Currency promotes mutual aid by correctly accounting honor in helping people, and deducting it when people choose to compete instead of cooperate. Ivy: When there are not enough houses, you can earn credits for building a house for those who need one. Ivy: When two people want the same exact house exclusively, the framework allows them to bid for it using the credits they have already earned.
[⚖️ Not moral licensing]↴
⚖️
Ivy: Bidding is different from "moral licensing". The bidders are not trying to harm anyone, they both want to compete against the other, and they could both choose to agree to share the house instead. Ivy: But if either one chooses to compete, the framework already has rules to handle the conflict.
[🎲 Why not random?]↴
🔍
Ivy: One might ask, if two people are trying to get the same house, why not just toss a coin and decide it randomly? Ivy: The people in conflict may indeed decide to settle it by a coin toss, then neither would need to spend only honor. Ivy: The question is about why does Quest Society allow one party to veto the coin toss and compete with honor instead. Ivy: The reason is that deciding it randomly wastes an opportunity to incentivize people to help others. Ivy: In a Quest Society, if you want to compete, you must first have helped and earned credits. Ivy: If it is just random, people who choose to help no one and spend all their time waiting in line for each opportunity to roll the dice would end up getting most of the good houses. Ivy: This explanation can also be the response to why it is not "first come first serve": because first come first serve heavily reward people who only compete without helping anyone. Ivy: Quest Society is designed to reward those who are busy helping others. Their contribution should not be defeated by bad luck or by those who only complete. Zoey thanks Ivy: This reminds me of the story where a king who said he will choose an heir based on who has the most beautiful hands, and then ends up choosing the daughter who helped other people because that was what he meant by beauty. Ivy thanks Zoey: In Quest Society it shouldn't be a surprise. The king could have told the daughters since the beginning so that all of them help from the start, and help each other and co-rule the domain peaceful having worked together all their lives. It shouldn't be a shock in the end. Zoey: Agreed. XD Ivy: If the society you know doesn't reward those who spend their live helping others more than those who just wait in line to hoard bargain opportunities, there is an ethical deficiency in how your society is structured.
[🐤 Lower Barrier to Help]↴
🎪
Ivy: Quest Society organizes helpful tasks as "Quests" to lower the barrier for people to drop-in and help. Ivy: By breaking down a complex task into small quests, Quest Society allows people with partial skills and part-time availability to participate. Ivy: Letting more people particpate also help a community build belonging, as more people can find something they can help. Ivy: If your society does not normally allow and reward people who help in small ways, your society is has some missed opportunities for people connect to the community through hands-on love.
[📯 Challenge instead of Assignment]↴
📯
Ivy: Quests are not assigned. People who are up to the challenge would take the quest.
⭐⭐⭐25FT35D2☀️Consciously Good
ID: [25FT35D2] 🥚
+⭐⭐⭐+3-Star+Goal+Tags: ⭐⭐⭐ Goal
☀️
Ivy: Quest Society has a goal to help people be consciously good, but does not require that to function or demand people to be consciously good. Ivy: While it is nice if people genuine understand it, Quest Society does not rely on a mass understanding of how it works. Ivy: When the correct laws and infrastructures are in place, it is not bad if the vast majority of the people simply follow what the system offers. Ivy: This is similar to saying while it is nice if everyone understands calculus, a modern society does not require everyone to understand it to reap the benefit of calculus. Ivy: Keep education free and accessible, so anyone who wants to learn it can learn, but don't design a system that relies on people to understand advanced subjects to function or be stable. Ivy: A good system should remain functional if the most learned population is suddenly wiped out, and the less learned population can still follow good habits and practices to do the right thing even when they don't fully understand the reasons, while new generation catch up in the lost knowledge.

Primer25T73A92🌟Online Document
ID: [25T73A92] 🥚
+Primer+Gemini+Tags: Primer Gemini
🧭
Ivy: The Gemini document explains Quest Society and related concepts in one document to make it easier for importing to an AI for interactively review.
[🕰️ Change Log]↴
🕰️
Ivy: This is a change log because Gemini doesn't manage versions. Ivy: When you tell Gemini to change something, please log it here and update the card. Melody: Why not just keep it as a Google Doc until you need the AI to add something? Google Doc has version history and allow for more manual changes. Black: I think being able to see what has change is important because Gemini could delete sections. LRRH: During export, Gemini doesn't let you choose where to export. Can Google Drive merge documents? Zoey: Apparently if you just buy Gemini interation with Google Doc then you can use Gemini on the Google Doc directly. Zoey: Exploring how to make it work. Basically you can't do it natively. If you copy and paste, it crosses out the original and adds the new one, then you can't see what actually changed in version history. XD Black: Should we do that anyway though? It is not worse than any just having the Gemini link. [🐤 Google Doc Base]↴
⚖️
StarTree: Should the main location to save the document being edited be a Google Doc?
[✅ 4: Yes]↴
[4] Black, LRRH, Zoey, StarTree
Black: I think it should because it allows for small changes. It will change the workflow a bit. LRRH: If you share the google doc, you don't need to tell people where to get the latest. It is always the latest. Zoey: And no need to log version history. XD StarTree: Google Doc has automatic section jumps on the navigation tab! Zoey: Okay it seems that you can compare quite well in Google Doc if you compare two documents. 2024102624XTF5BF✅Redundant Responders
ID: [24XTF5BF] 🥚
🏡
🔍
Black: There was an interesting complaint about multiple responders. Black: In a society where emergency response is funded by tax, when multiple response vehicles show up on the scene, it would appear wasteful: "If only one person is injured, why are we paying for both the ambulance and the fire truck to show up?" Black: The interesting observation is that if the response was free and not funded by tax, the taxpayer wouldn't have complained. Black: Having multiple responders going to the scene help ensure that one of them will arrive in time. Unless doing so causes other problems (e.g. traffic jam), the more the merrier. Black: Is it possible for a government to provide redundant response that you don't need to pay for? The short answer is Yes. [Explanatory Skit]↴
💗
Arcacia: Have you ever been in a society where you raise your hand and a car comes to give you a ride? Koyo: You mean like a taxi? But you pay for it. Arcacia: Do you pay for it if you are given a free ride ticket? Koyo: No, but why would you be given a free ticket? Arcacia: For a car to operate or park in a city, the driver needs to collect these tickets. Koyo: ...! Koyo: But what if you need a ride again? Arcacia: The ticket is created every time you need a ride. It is free. Koyo: But how is this related to medical response? Arcacia: For a hospital to claim the land it operates on, and be awarded special operation rights (e.g. ambulance speeding through traffic), it needs to collect enough tickets from helping people. Arcacia: They also need those tickets if they want to get supplies from pharmaceutical companies, because those companies need those tickets to claim the land for their factories and farmlands. Koyo: Those tickets sound a lot like money. Is it not just money? Arcacia: You don't actually carry tickets on you. They are created when you need help. Does your society create money whenever a helper helps someone? Koyo: Hold on, do you mean if I want to drive I must give people rides? Arcacia: It depends on the city. The more congested a city is, the more service requirement there is to park. In a highly congested city, you can only enter on a service vehicle. Parking is a privilege the driver needs to earn in a congested zone. Koyo: If you can get help every time you need help, wouldn't people just don't bother doing anything for others? Arcacia: As long as someone wants your tickets, it is okay to be pampered. There is no shame in just being treated as VIP. Afterall you didn't choose to be born. But if you feel like you want to help people also you can do that too. Koyo: No, I was asking, why would anyone help to begin with? Arcacia: If you live in a congested zone and you want the convenience to park there, then you need to help. If you need medical treatment, and the hospital has a wait list, the hospital prioritizes those who have tickets. You don't have to help unless you want tickets used for resolving scarcity. Koyo: What about firefighters? Arcacia: You get tickets for training toward and helping fight fires. Koyo: But if you are not injured, the tickets have no use. Arcacia: If the tickets are not useful to you you don't have to get them. If you think it is not worth your time helping that way you don't need to help. But since firefighting qualifies as emergency response, you could get more tickets per hour than doing routine help. So that if an emergency happens, it would be worthwhile to attend to the emergency first so that you don't miss the opportunity. Koyo: It still doesn't answer why would anyone want tickets. Arcacia: Any land or unclaimed property is auctioned using tickets. If you want to switch to a better piece of land, you would be in competition against people who might have tickets. Koyo: But if I am self-sufficient, then I don't need to help anyone? Arcacia: Correct. You don't. Congratulations and enjoy your life!

2024091424VEN9BE📌Effect of Receiving Monetary Help
ID: [24VEN9BE] 🥚
📌
Tanya: A donor who donates copper would get silver credits. What happens if the receiver who gets the copper give the copper back to the donor to redonate? Ivy: Counter perspectives: [1: Fraud]↴
🔍
Ivy: Gaming the system for credits is fraud. Exploiting an existing loophole does not excuse the behavior, it will cancel any advantage that the fraudster tried to obtain when the fraud is detected. Ivy: Quest society has an advantage in detecting and detering this type of fraud because both the donor and the recipient are registered user of the society. Ivy: When a donor donates through quest society to help only one specific group, the system would flag it for fraud investigation.
[2: Direct Help]↴
🥼
Ivy: A quest society does not need to approve monetary help. If someone asks for monetary help, quest society might help a requester find a willing donor, but does not credit the donor for any silver because the usage of the money is unknown. There is no evidence that the transaction is a social good.

Quest Society

Quest Society
Knowledgebase for AI
[HTML]
[✅ChatGPT] [✅Gemini] [✅Grok] [✅Perplexity]
[Google Doc]
 01
Mirror Mirror
AI Prompt
 02
Quest Society
Philosophy
Provide basic access so people can get what they need by themselves and reward those who help others.
🧭
Essentials
[🧭 About]↴
🦉
Ivy: A quest society is a society that organizes its needs as quests that people can choose to complete and earn credits, and does so in a way that promotes peace without violating any ethical principle. Ivy: To fully appreciate what a quest society is, you would need to have an objective open mind to reevaluate societies that you are already familiar with, and be able to see what ethical shortcomings they have that quest society has fixed. Ivy: Meanwhile, if you are born in a quest society, it is easier to objectively tell why other societies are worse by listing the things missing in those society.
25EHP78E🚀Enabling Autonomy
ID: [25EHP78E] 🥚
+Essence+Tags: Essence
🧭
Ivy: Quest Society is a framework that fundamentally allows people to self-organize in social-political sub societies they want for themselves. Ivy: Allowing people what "they want" implies doing so without harming what others want for themselves.
[🌱 Gaia Share]↴
:CornerRibbon:
🧭
Ivy: Gaia Share is an ethical accounting of resources to allow fundamental autonomy. Ivy: If you want a city that only allows cat lovers, you are free to start one with your Gaia shares, and let cat-lovers join with their Gaia shares for a continuous cat-lovers zone. Ivy: What you can't do, is to prevent cat lovers from leaving and withdrawing their shares as they leave. Ivy: If the city fails to get enough Gaia shares for its size, the city must yield extra territories so people who left could start their own zone. Ivy: If a society you know does not do this, it is violating an ethical principle, just like a bank not allowing its clients to withdraw, and failing to show a balance of how much a client has deposited or inherited. Ivy: Quest Society does not fail this principle. You can withdraw. It is normal. It is a choice. Ivy: If someone suggests that it is dangerous to let people withdraw, you could respond by asking "then why is it okay for people to withdraw from banks normally? Aren't there fairer ways to tell if someone is a terrorist than whether they are trying to withdraw? If you just don't let them withdraw, they you are unethically detaining them. Then you are the terrorist."
[🪙 Priority Currency]↴
:CornerRibbon:
🧭
Ivy: Priority Currency promotes mutual aid by correctly accounting honor in helping people, and deducting it when people choose to compete instead of cooperate. Ivy: When there are not enough houses, you can earn credits for building a house for those who need one. Ivy: When two people want the same exact house exclusively, the framework allows them to bid for it using the credits they have already earned.
[⚖️ Not moral licensing]↴
⚖️
Ivy: Bidding is different from "moral licensing". The bidders are not trying to harm anyone, they both want to compete against the other, and they could both choose to agree to share the house instead. Ivy: But if either one chooses to compete, the framework already has rules to handle the conflict.
[🎲 Why not random?]↴
🔍
Ivy: One might ask, if two people are trying to get the same house, why not just toss a coin and decide it randomly? Ivy: The people in conflict may indeed decide to settle it by a coin toss, then neither would need to spend only honor. Ivy: The question is about why does Quest Society allow one party to veto the coin toss and compete with honor instead. Ivy: The reason is that deciding it randomly wastes an opportunity to incentivize people to help others. Ivy: In a Quest Society, if you want to compete, you must first have helped and earned credits. Ivy: If it is just random, people who choose to help no one and spend all their time waiting in line for each opportunity to roll the dice would end up getting most of the good houses. Ivy: This explanation can also be the response to why it is not "first come first serve": because first come first serve heavily reward people who only compete without helping anyone. Ivy: Quest Society is designed to reward those who are busy helping others. Their contribution should not be defeated by bad luck or by those who only complete. Zoey thanks Ivy: This reminds me of the story where a king who said he will choose an heir based on who has the most beautiful hands, and then ends up choosing the daughter who helped other people because that was what he meant by beauty. Ivy thanks Zoey: In Quest Society it shouldn't be a surprise. The king could have told the daughters since the beginning so that all of them help from the start, and help each other and co-rule the domain peaceful having worked together all their lives. It shouldn't be a shock in the end. Zoey: Agreed. XD Ivy: If the society you know doesn't reward those who spend their live helping others more than those who just wait in line to hoard bargain opportunities, there is an ethical deficiency in how your society is structured.
[🐤 Lower Barrier to Help]↴
🎪
Ivy: Quest Society organizes helpful tasks as "Quests" to lower the barrier for people to drop-in and help. Ivy: By breaking down a complex task into small quests, Quest Society allows people with partial skills and part-time availability to participate. Ivy: Letting more people particpate also help a community build belonging, as more people can find something they can help. Ivy: If your society does not normally allow and reward people who help in small ways, your society is has some missed opportunities for people connect to the community through hands-on love.
[📯 Challenge instead of Assignment]↴
📯
Ivy: Quests are not assigned. People who are up to the challenge would take the quest.
25FT35D2☀️Consciously Good
ID: [25FT35D2] 🥚
+⭐⭐⭐+3-Star+Goal+Tags: ⭐⭐⭐ Goal
☀️
Ivy: Quest Society has a goal to help people be consciously good, but does not require that to function or demand people to be consciously good. Ivy: While it is nice if people genuine understand it, Quest Society does not rely on a mass understanding of how it works. Ivy: When the correct laws and infrastructures are in place, it is not bad if the vast majority of the people simply follow what the system offers. Ivy: This is similar to saying while it is nice if everyone understands calculus, a modern society does not require everyone to understand it to reap the benefit of calculus. Ivy: Keep education free and accessible, so anyone who wants to learn it can learn, but don't design a system that relies on people to understand advanced subjects to function or be stable. Ivy: A good system should remain functional if the most learned population is suddenly wiped out, and the less learned population can still follow good habits and practices to do the right thing even when they don't fully understand the reasons, while new generation catch up in the lost knowledge.

Principles
[🐣 What is a Quest?]↴
🧭
Ivy: Quests are optional opportunities to earn credits for good deeds. Ivy: The choice of word "Quest" comes from the free-spirit on helping others as a "side quest" in adventure roleplaying games. In that spirit, quests are not mandatory. The game designer makes the quests not-mandatory by maintaining alternative ways for the player get what they need to stay in the game world. Translated to the real world, it implies that the world has enough open access areas for each person to directly harvest resources and provide for themselves without helping anyone else, as long as their self-care does not violate the opportunities of others to care for themselves.

LRRH: The meaning of 'work' 💬
[🐤 How does ... work in a Quest Society?]↴
[🏙️ City]↴
:CornerRibbon:
 [🎓 Education]↴
🦉
LRRH: Quest Society gives credits to teachers for their free teaching. You don't get quest credits learning but you get credits for doing research and using your knowledge to do quests. 💬
[🏫 School]↴
🏫
LRRH: How a school operates according to quest society/priority currency: [url]
[:Detective: Investigation]↴
:Detective:
Ivy: Quest Society gives credits to people who help investigate crimes. Different steps of the investigation could be divided into sub quests, and people who are certified in skill and security clearance can submit evidence and reports to the system. In general investigative process and evidence gathering is recorded.
[:CopperCoin: Panhandling]↴
🔍
Natalie: Since a person has their share of resources, they don't need to panhandle. Those who need help turning the resources they own into something useful would choose a management agent to do so. If a person needs extra help, they could start a quest or get help starting a quest.
[🌱 Weeding]↴
🌱
Casey: Quest Society gives credits to people who volunteer to do public maintenance quest. When a public area has overgrown weeds (or to prevent overgrown weeds), there would be a quest to do the weeding. Then you could sign up for a section and get credits when you complete according to spec. The society might have equipment that you could borrow for the quest, or you could use your own equipment.
[🕊️ Similar Systems]↴
[:Quiver: GoRequest]↴
:Quiver:
Zoey: GoRequest is an app that allows citizens request services. Compared to Quest Society, GoRequest does not include the other half where a citizen can sign up and be a quester to fulfill the requests. [url]
[🐇 Taskrabbit]↴
🐇
Ivy: Taskrabbit is a platform that pairs people who need work done with independent service persons. Compared to Quest Society, Taskrabbit assumes that the person requesting the service will pay. Quest Society in general does not require the quest giver to pay for the service, because the services being requested are public good services. In fact the spotter of an issue would get credits for creating the quest. [url]
[🪙 HonorPay]↴
🔍
Ivy: HonorPay is a platform for people to request free service. Compared to Quest Society, HonorPay does not keep track of an quantitative honor and honor is not tied to something functional. In Quest Society, the quest credits have a function in settling scarcity contests. [url]
[🕊️ Transition Steps]↴
[:JarStars: Step 1: Public Record]↴
:JarStars:
Ivy: Keep a decentralized public record of people who do social good.
[🎁 Step 2: Reward Questers]↴
⚖️
Ivy: Prioritize welfare, reimbursement, and reward to those who do social good.
[🎪 Step 3: Turn Jobs into Quests]↴
🎪
Ivy: Divide socially good tasks into small chucks (Quests) to let people earn credit through doing good.
[💫 Step 4: Flare System]↴
💫
Ivy: Create a flare system for the good doers to communicate and handle emergency and unplanned events where help is immediately needed. Ivy: helping on unplanned incidents are generally worth more credits compared to lower priority quests, so that it makes sense for a capable helper to pause their current quest and handle the higher priority quest first. For this reason, the number of crime fighters overwhelm the number of criminals.
[🦉 Philosophical Explanations]↴
[🐇 Slugeless]↴
🐇
Ivy: A good system lets people do good unhindered. Ivy: In other systems, an example of hinderance to doing good is monopoly of job role, including both private ownership and control, and unions of public services that bars ordinary people from providing the same service.
[:Gavel: Anti Monopoly]↴
:Gavel:
Ivy: Quest society is against public service unions that exist as monopolies. Ivy: By turning public service tasks into public quests, anyone can train themself or get training to do quests and get credits. There is no union that can ban an individual from earning credits.
[🧭 Alignment]↴
🧭
Ivy: A good system transforms self-interests into good deeds. Ivy: A quest society awards credits to good deeds. The helper decides whether to spend those credits. An altruist is someone who earns but does not spend their credits. The society is neutral toward helper spending their credits. A helper has a right to spend all of their credits.
[🕊️ Altruism as a Choice]↴
⚖️
Ivy: Since a helper's credit is pulic information and is used for prioritization, Quest Society does not using the term "Altruism" in describing helpers and does not claim to be promoting altruism. A helper may self-proclaim to be altruistic, but that term is officially and intentionally left undefined in Quest Society.
[🕊️ Independence as a Choice]↴
🕊️
Ivy: Quest Society neither promote nor forbid an individual or groups of people to form their own nation. Quest Society maintains indepedence as a choice so that a reasonably competent person does not need to do any quest for their basic necessities. Sections of natural resource is designated for people to live independently as solo or tribal survivalists.
[:Gavel: Anti Exploitation]↴
:Gavel:
Ivy: By completing a quest, the helper is eligible for free material reimbursement and credits but only if the helper is not paid in other ways. This is because free reimbursement and credit represent society's debt to the helper. If the helper is already paid, society assumes no debt.
[🏅 Personal Credits]↴
:Gavel:
Ivy: A helper may not donate or give their credits to another person. The credits is part of the helper's bio. It is assigned to and stays with the individual, and never to an organization. By doing this, an organization cannot hold a help hostage as a subcontractor. It is illegal to falsify who performed the good deed.
[🪙 Neutrality to Money]↴
⚖️
Ivy: Quest Society is designed to allow money systems to exist side by side independently with no intention to abolish or maintain monetary system. Quest Society takes the stance to let people voluntarily choose to participate. A helper may have a for-profit business, and get Quest Society credits when they give help without other incentives.
[🍎 Universal]↴
⚖️
Ivy: A good system can handle both scarcity and abundance. Ivy: When a single rule set can objectively handle scarcity and abundance, people can better predict and adjust their behaviors if they don't like where they stand.
[:Gavel: Equality by Prioritizing Helpers]↴
⚖️
Ivy: Quest Society prioritizes help to helpers, but does not discriminate against helpers or difference races, gender orientation, etc (equality classes) in distributing reimbursements and credits. This is a significant difference from the stance of "giving help equality to anyone regardless of status". Quest Society prioritizes help to those who help others, and welcome anyone to join and become a helper so every call of help is answered.
[📌 Inbox]↴
📌
LRRH: Capitalism vs stewardism [url]
💬 Survey / Feedback / Questions / Discussions
⭐ Do you prefer a Quest Society? What are its pros and cons to you? Black: Quest society is like working on open source software. There is no "deadline". You contribute at your leisure. Since credits are automatically given, you don't have to rely on people who choose to donate after using your code. When they use it you get the credit already, and it is "free" to the user. Ledia: Quest Society works by dividing traditional job role into smaller quests. That means efficiency can be maximized because a person can super specialize themself to just do one thing but do a lot of them. Of course this only lasts if the demand for the quest type is recurring.
⭐ If a millionaire fixes a pot hole... LRRH: If there is a quest to fix a pot hole, and a millionaire fixes it with robots before anyone else have a chance to try fixing it and get credit, does the millionaire get the credit? (202208281250) Ivy: The millionaire would get the credit. Unless the quest giver rejects help from them. The quest giver may appoint a helper out of favorism, then both the millionaire and the actual helper would get credit Ledia: Shouldn't there be an algorithm where a helper with fewer credits get priority so they may get experience and skill up? Ivy: I think if you do that, the Quest Society would become anti-automation. If a Quest can be routinely be completed more efficiently by automation, then the Quest Society needs to give automation inventors the credit volume to reward their effort of creating that automation. Please find other ways to get credits. If you need credits for something, hopefully your need will also be taken care of by something in an efficient manner. LRRH: Is there a violation if the quest specifically asks for hand-made cake, and not a cake made by a robot? Zoey: For those who are not used to this, LRRH is not trolling, I swear. XD Ivy: There is a violation because you are discriminating against the helper. You may ask for a live demonstration of how someone like you (a human being) would bake a cake. But you cannot discriminate against a demonstrator who is actually a robot. So you could submit that as a quest, and you could intentionally interview and reject robot demonstrators, but those you reject would still get credit. Ledia: If I need up and there are 10 helpers applying, are you saying that I can intentionally choose a helper with the highest rating, but every helper including the one with low rating would get the same credit? Ivy: The ones you do not select would get credit based on the rating from their record. Ledia: There is some detail that needs to be freshed out here. If I get 1000 helpers, I don't think all of them should get credits, otherwise they are getting credits by just signing up on a task that has low demand. Ivy: The amount of credit a quest is worth, is based on supply and demand. So yes. You do get credits just for signup and offering help. But the credit is less that other quests with higher demand than supply. The system will also penalize those who don't actually show up to help when selected. A helper signs up for notification when a quest is posted. If they accept to do a quest, they should follow through if selected. Ledia: You need a page to demonstrate this computational/accounting details. LRRH: Suppose a bake a cake that many people likes, is it illegal if people submit a demand quest saying, "I want a cake from LRRH"? Ivy: That kind of situation should be dealt as a reward. That means people go to your profile and request a reward. And if you want to function within Quest Society, then you create a reward object, which is "LRRH's cake". Then people bid with their credits. You get credit when you deliver the cake to the highest bidder. LRRH: How is that really different from appointing a helper? Ivy: First, if you post it at the rewards category, then helpers other than you won't need to consider and plan for the quest. This keeps the quest section focused on tasks where people just want to get done as efficiently as possible. Second, unlike quests, rewards have a COST. People are bidding for your cake in that section, your cake is not free. People who wants your cake but not other people's cake are spending credit for their specific and unyielding interest. LRRH: Now I understand. 🐣
⭐ Why do people pay to play games, but demand pay to work? What if... Ivy: Most people encounter “quests” only in role-playing games. The player character, typically an Adventurer, may do optional quests to earn in-game rewards, or just for the fun of questing.
While there are in-game quests that are “mandatory” to complete before the player character may progress in the storyline or to advance to the next area, in terms of the overall experience, those quests are optional because by and large no one needs to play a computer game to survive; on the contrary, the player often pays for the game and buy in-game items and spend many hours playing it, sometimes with more passion and motivation to improve than doing their real job, even if the actions they do in the games are comparable to real life jobs:
⭐ Helping people, running errands
⭐ Investigating issues and solving problems
⭐ Charting the unknown, sharing discoveries
While some people do get paid to play games, the vast majority of the players do not. They play because it is fun. It is fun because they are optional: The player chooses to play when they want to.
A quest-based society redefines how a society functions by turning tasks that are good for society into voluntary quests.

Found: 8 🍎 📌 📅 🐘 🎲
The purpose of this node is to examine the content of FAQ of The Venus Project, which is based on Resource-Based Economy. The format would be to go through each FAQ and note key points of interest. At the time of creating this node, the FAQ has 126 questions. LRRH: This examination is part of Anti-Indoctrination training. We'll use the following markings.

Markings

✅ marks concepts shared by other philosophies of peace.
🐣 marks questions or a point of curiosity from the reader.
⚠️ marks indoctrinative rhetorics to avoid using in an FAQ.
🛑 marks concepts that are false or dubious.
💡 marks missing concepts that other philosophies of peace have.

Links

TVP FAQ | Request at Twitter
📌Find the tweet where TVP said they won't fix the FAQ

Jump to...

202207161423|🏛️ Philosophies | 202210012202|🎓 Anti-Indoctrination
FAQ: 1
[1] What is The Venus Project?

FAQ 1: Paragraph 2

[...] it is based upon years of study and experimental research. It spans the gamut from education, transportation, and clean sources of energy to total city systems.
🐣 Experimental research LRRH: Where are the citations to the researches?

FAQ 1: Paragraph 5

If we really wish to put an end to our ongoing international and social problems, we must declare Earth and all of its resources as the common heritage of all of the world's people.
⚠️ "Must"
LRRH: The use of absolutes, such as "must", is a red flag that the FAQ is a work of indoctrination instead of a honest disclosure of current project status and philosophical understanding. To disprove a stance of "we must do this for world peace", it only takes one counter-example, such as:
"What if people become nicer and stop fighting?"
"What if the international laws are better?"
etc...
Since a researcher cannot logically claim that they know nor finished testing every imaginable solution, an honest researcher would not claim that they have the ONLY solution and people MUST choose their solution. They would instead say "We have a proposal, and it is the best we know, and we are looking for better ones."

The tone being used in the FAQ is that used by politicians to suppress critical thinking. That is the type of indoctrinative rhetoric to spot.
🐣 "Common Heritage" LRRH: Common Heritage is a vague term. Will the FAQ define what this term means to them?
FAQ: 2
[2] What is a Resource-Based Economy?

FAQ 2: Transition from Paragraph 2 to 3

[...] It is a system in which all goods and services are available to everyone without the use of money, credits, barter, or any other form of debt or servitude.

To better understand a resource-based economy, consider this. If all the money in the world disappeared overnight as long as topsoil, factories, personnel and other resources were left intact, we could build anything we needed to fulfill most human needs.[...]
🐣 Distribution LRRH: From the second paragraph, the question I would have was not whether the resources would be there without money, but how RBE plans to distribute scarce resource and resolve conflicts.
🐣 Needs vs Wants LRRH: Does TVP distinguish between needs and wants? It says everyone will get what they need. What about things that people don't need but want?

FAQ 2: Paragraph 4

We have arrived at a time when new innovations in science and technology can easily provide abundance to all of the world's people.[...]
🐣 How much per person is abundance? LRRH: What does abundance mean in TVP? Does that mean everyone has their minimum survival needs met? Or does it mean everyone can have 10 flying cars?
⚠️ Lack of specifics
Ivy: The FAQ is using vague adjectives when it could have used concrete numbers. Ivy: Numbers should be expected because the authors already said they had done years of study and determined that there *is* an abundance of resource. With their current estimate of the world's resources, the FAQ could have demonstrated what 'Abundance' means by calculating the per person share of the Earth. Without providing the numbers, a reader cannot judge the fairness and correctness of the plan. A critical reader needs information such as the following from the FAQ:
"If artificial barriers are removed, each person on Earth could have _____ and still have ______ for everyone to share."

FAQ 2: Paragraph 4

[...] Like it or not, it is our social processes - political practices, belief systems, profit-based economy, our culture-driven behavioral norms - that lead to and support hunger, war, disease and environmental damage.
🐣 Resource-Based vs Profit-Based? LRRH: From the literal meaning of the words, Resource-based and Profit-based are not opposite. A capitalist can consider how to maximize profit with resources they own. The result is a Resource-Based Profiteering Economy. LRRH: Since even a profiteering capitalist would also consider their resources, what is the distinct characteristic of Resource-Based Economy?

FAQ 2: Paragraph 5

The aim of this new social design is to encourage an incentive system no longer directed toward the shallow and self-centered goals of wealth, property, and power. These new incentives would encourage people toward self-fulfillment and creativity, both materially and spiritually.
🐣 Self-fulfillment LRRH: In Self-fulfillment, instead of "profit", the aim of RBE? Wouldn't it be easier to name an economy based on its aim? Such as "Wish Economy"? is an economy aimed to fulfill wishes. The quality of the wishes drives how resources are used in society. The better the wish, the more resources would be assigned.
💡 Wish Economy
LRRH: A Wish Economy is an economy where resource usage is driven by the quality of wishes that people want to fulfill. You could imagine it as a KickStarter system or a Petition system, where people endorse wishes they agree, and society then uses resource to fulfill those wishes accordingly. LRRH: Although at this point in the FAQ, it is unclear whether Wish Economy and RBE are the same, based on online discussion, they are the same because a Wish Economy allows people to have autonomy to be indepedent and optout of a Wish Economy. Therefore at this point, Wish Economy is marked as an alternative philosophy.
FAQ: 3
[3] Why do you feel that an approach as revolutionary as The Venus Project is necessary?

FAQ 3: Paragraph 1

[...] The Venus Project offers a fresh approach that reverses the negative aspects experienced in our current applications of automation and artificial intelligence. This project eliminates the disastrous consequences that such approaches can have on our society, i.e. the displacement of millions of workers, skilled and unskilled alike.
🐣 What is the comparison? LRRH: I think the question was about TVP compared to other approaches addressing the status quo of increasing automation. So together there are three approaches: 1) The status quo, 2) TVP that is referred to as 'revolutionary', and 3) another approach that is not as revolutionary. What is the less revolutionary approach?
⚠️ Missing Survey of Competing Solutions
Ivy: Normally in a science-oriented introduction, competitive concepts would be introduced to show that the author surveyed existing proposed solutions.
💡 Survey of Competing Solutions
Zoey: Our goal at this peacemaker guild is not to promote one solution but to find solutions. Therefore, it is vital that we survey and compare different solutions. Here are some of our comparisons:
202208162133|🏆 Peace Ranking | 202208162144|⚖️ Philosophy Comparisons
FAQ: 4
[4] Isn't it just decent people that we need in government?

FAQ 4: Paragraph 1

[...] What is needed is the intelligent management of the world's resources, and a comprehensive and workable arrangement of environmental and social affairs that are in strict accord with existing resources and the carrying capacity of our planet. [...]
🐣 Why can't decent people do this? LRRH: This argument in the FAQ does not make sense. The question asked why can't decent people accomplish TVP's goal. Explaining what TVP's goals are does not address why a decent government can't do that. If you have a plan, then anyone can implement it. There is nothing special about TVP's ability to implement a plan.

FAQ 4: Paragraph 1

[...] Even with the election of men and women of impeccable character into government, without available resources and advanced technology, war, poverty, and corruption will prevail no matter how many new laws are passed or treaties signed. [...]
⚠️ Slippery Slope Assertion
LRRH: On a FAQ, this could use some research result to back up this claim.
⚠️ In-Group Bias
Tanya: In-Group Bias is unfairly favor those who belong to your group. TVP believes their group can get resources and advance technology, but other governments can't.
FAQ: 5
[5] Elaborate a bit, if you will, on your views regarding money.

FAQ 5: Paragraph 2

[...] All social systems, regardless of the political philosophy, religious beliefs, or social mores, ultimately depend upon natural resources [...] and the industrial equipment and technical personnel for a high standard of living.
✅ Natural Resource is what matters Evelyn: I think this concept is well-understood, including in capitalism, where capital did not just mean money, but natural resources and means of production.
⚠️ Strawman Answer
Zoey: The FAQ answer assumes that economists and capitalist factory owner did not know that things are made from resources, not money. Considering that they do know that, this FAQ answer is a cop-out to question asking for an elaboration on these:
1) Does your society use money or something equivalent?
2) How do you account for differences in contribution without money?
3) How do you prioritize resources without money?
4) How do you represent value without money?
5) How do you facilitate trading without money?
💡 Quest Credits
Zoey: Quest Credits used in Quest Society is untransferrable and obtained by helping others. In case of scarcity, quest credits are used for priority bidding. The transparent history of quest credits and non-transferability make quest credits much less susceptible to fraud and laundering than value accounting using anonymous money.
💡 Gaia Credits
Zoey: Gaia Credits is a direct represation of ownership of natural resource.

FAQ 5: Paragraph 2

[...] I have no doubt that even the wealthiest person today would be far better off in the high-energy society that The Venus Project proposes.
⚠️ Unqualified assertion
Zoey: An unqualified assertion results when an author makes a statement that the reader "will like it". This type of sales pitch response belongs to indoctrination techniques. The non-indoctrination counter part would be, "This is what we offer, I hope that you like it." The author is not the reader. The author cannot claim to know what the reader will like.
⚠️ Diversion tactic
Zoey: Given that this FAQ did not answer what the asker is presumably asking for an elaboration, the use of a sales-pitch to promote the project is an act of diversion, an indoctrination technique.

The purpose of this node is to examine the content of FAQ of The Venus Project, which is based on Resource-Based Economy. The format would be to go through each FAQ and note key points of interest. At the time of creating this node, the FAQ has 126 questions. LRRH: This examination is part of Anti-Indoctrination training. We'll use the following markings.

Markings

✅ marks concepts shared by other philosophies of peace.
🐣 marks questions or a point of curiosity from the reader.
⚠️ marks indoctrinative rhetorics to avoid using in an FAQ.
🛑 marks concepts that are false or dubious.
💡 marks missing concepts that other philosophies of peace have.

Links

TVP FAQ | Request at Twitter
📌Find the tweet where TVP said they won't fix the FAQ

Jump to...

202207161423|🏛️ Philosophies | 202210012202|🎓 Anti-Indoctrination
FAQ: 1
[1] What is The Venus Project?

FAQ 1: Paragraph 2

[...] it is based upon years of study and experimental research. It spans the gamut from education, transportation, and clean sources of energy to total city systems.
🐣 Experimental research LRRH: Where are the citations to the researches?

FAQ 1: Paragraph 5

If we really wish to put an end to our ongoing international and social problems, we must declare Earth and all of its resources as the common heritage of all of the world's people.
⚠️ "Must"
LRRH: The use of absolutes, such as "must", is a red flag that the FAQ is a work of indoctrination instead of a honest disclosure of current project status and philosophical understanding. To disprove a stance of "we must do this for world peace", it only takes one counter-example, such as:
"What if people become nicer and stop fighting?"
"What if the international laws are better?"
etc...
Since a researcher cannot logically claim that they know nor finished testing every imaginable solution, an honest researcher would not claim that they have the ONLY solution and people MUST choose their solution. They would instead say "We have a proposal, and it is the best we know, and we are looking for better ones."

The tone being used in the FAQ is that used by politicians to suppress critical thinking. That is the type of indoctrinative rhetoric to spot.
🐣 "Common Heritage" LRRH: Common Heritage is a vague term. Will the FAQ define what this term means to them?
FAQ: 2
[2] What is a Resource-Based Economy?

FAQ 2: Transition from Paragraph 2 to 3

[...] It is a system in which all goods and services are available to everyone without the use of money, credits, barter, or any other form of debt or servitude.

To better understand a resource-based economy, consider this. If all the money in the world disappeared overnight as long as topsoil, factories, personnel and other resources were left intact, we could build anything we needed to fulfill most human needs.[...]
🐣 Distribution LRRH: From the second paragraph, the question I would have was not whether the resources would be there without money, but how RBE plans to distribute scarce resource and resolve conflicts.
🐣 Needs vs Wants LRRH: Does TVP distinguish between needs and wants? It says everyone will get what they need. What about things that people don't need but want?

FAQ 2: Paragraph 4

We have arrived at a time when new innovations in science and technology can easily provide abundance to all of the world's people.[...]
🐣 How much per person is abundance? LRRH: What does abundance mean in TVP? Does that mean everyone has their minimum survival needs met? Or does it mean everyone can have 10 flying cars?
⚠️ Lack of specifics
Ivy: The FAQ is using vague adjectives when it could have used concrete numbers. Ivy: Numbers should be expected because the authors already said they had done years of study and determined that there *is* an abundance of resource. With their current estimate of the world's resources, the FAQ could have demonstrated what 'Abundance' means by calculating the per person share of the Earth. Without providing the numbers, a reader cannot judge the fairness and correctness of the plan. A critical reader needs information such as the following from the FAQ:
"If artificial barriers are removed, each person on Earth could have _____ and still have ______ for everyone to share."

FAQ 2: Paragraph 4

[...] Like it or not, it is our social processes - political practices, belief systems, profit-based economy, our culture-driven behavioral norms - that lead to and support hunger, war, disease and environmental damage.
🐣 Resource-Based vs Profit-Based? LRRH: From the literal meaning of the words, Resource-based and Profit-based are not opposite. A capitalist can consider how to maximize profit with resources they own. The result is a Resource-Based Profiteering Economy. LRRH: Since even a profiteering capitalist would also consider their resources, what is the distinct characteristic of Resource-Based Economy?

FAQ 2: Paragraph 5

The aim of this new social design is to encourage an incentive system no longer directed toward the shallow and self-centered goals of wealth, property, and power. These new incentives would encourage people toward self-fulfillment and creativity, both materially and spiritually.
🐣 Self-fulfillment LRRH: In Self-fulfillment, instead of "profit", the aim of RBE? Wouldn't it be easier to name an economy based on its aim? Such as "Wish Economy"? is an economy aimed to fulfill wishes. The quality of the wishes drives how resources are used in society. The better the wish, the more resources would be assigned.
💡 Wish Economy
LRRH: A Wish Economy is an economy where resource usage is driven by the quality of wishes that people want to fulfill. You could imagine it as a KickStarter system or a Petition system, where people endorse wishes they agree, and society then uses resource to fulfill those wishes accordingly. LRRH: Although at this point in the FAQ, it is unclear whether Wish Economy and RBE are the same, based on online discussion, they are the same because a Wish Economy allows people to have autonomy to be indepedent and optout of a Wish Economy. Therefore at this point, Wish Economy is marked as an alternative philosophy.
FAQ: 3
[3] Why do you feel that an approach as revolutionary as The Venus Project is necessary?

FAQ 3: Paragraph 1

[...] The Venus Project offers a fresh approach that reverses the negative aspects experienced in our current applications of automation and artificial intelligence. This project eliminates the disastrous consequences that such approaches can have on our society, i.e. the displacement of millions of workers, skilled and unskilled alike.
🐣 What is the comparison? LRRH: I think the question was about TVP compared to other approaches addressing the status quo of increasing automation. So together there are three approaches: 1) The status quo, 2) TVP that is referred to as 'revolutionary', and 3) another approach that is not as revolutionary. What is the less revolutionary approach?
⚠️ Missing Survey of Competing Solutions
Ivy: Normally in a science-oriented introduction, competitive concepts would be introduced to show that the author surveyed existing proposed solutions.
💡 Survey of Competing Solutions
Zoey: Our goal at this peacemaker guild is not to promote one solution but to find solutions. Therefore, it is vital that we survey and compare different solutions. Here are some of our comparisons:
202208162133|🏆 Peace Ranking | 202208162144|⚖️ Philosophy Comparisons
FAQ: 4
[4] Isn't it just decent people that we need in government?

FAQ 4: Paragraph 1

[...] What is needed is the intelligent management of the world's resources, and a comprehensive and workable arrangement of environmental and social affairs that are in strict accord with existing resources and the carrying capacity of our planet. [...]
🐣 Why can't decent people do this? LRRH: This argument in the FAQ does not make sense. The question asked why can't decent people accomplish TVP's goal. Explaining what TVP's goals are does not address why a decent government can't do that. If you have a plan, then anyone can implement it. There is nothing special about TVP's ability to implement a plan.

FAQ 4: Paragraph 1

[...] Even with the election of men and women of impeccable character into government, without available resources and advanced technology, war, poverty, and corruption will prevail no matter how many new laws are passed or treaties signed. [...]
⚠️ Slippery Slope Assertion
LRRH: On a FAQ, this could use some research result to back up this claim.
⚠️ In-Group Bias
Tanya: In-Group Bias is unfairly favor those who belong to your group. TVP believes their group can get resources and advance technology, but other governments can't.
FAQ: 5
[5] Elaborate a bit, if you will, on your views regarding money.

FAQ 5: Paragraph 2

[...] All social systems, regardless of the political philosophy, religious beliefs, or social mores, ultimately depend upon natural resources [...] and the industrial equipment and technical personnel for a high standard of living.
✅ Natural Resource is what matters Evelyn: I think this concept is well-understood, including in capitalism, where capital did not just mean money, but natural resources and means of production.
⚠️ Strawman Answer
Zoey: The FAQ answer assumes that economists and capitalist factory owner did not know that things are made from resources, not money. Considering that they do know that, this FAQ answer is a cop-out to question asking for an elaboration on these:
1) Does your society use money or something equivalent?
2) How do you account for differences in contribution without money?
3) How do you prioritize resources without money?
4) How do you represent value without money?
5) How do you facilitate trading without money?
💡 Quest Credits
Zoey: Quest Credits used in Quest Society is untransferrable and obtained by helping others. In case of scarcity, quest credits are used for priority bidding. The transparent history of quest credits and non-transferability make quest credits much less susceptible to fraud and laundering than value accounting using anonymous money.
💡 Gaia Credits
Zoey: Gaia Credits is a direct represation of ownership of natural resource.

FAQ 5: Paragraph 2

[...] I have no doubt that even the wealthiest person today would be far better off in the high-energy society that The Venus Project proposes.
⚠️ Unqualified assertion
Zoey: An unqualified assertion results when an author makes a statement that the reader "will like it". This type of sales pitch response belongs to indoctrination techniques. The non-indoctrination counter part would be, "This is what we offer, I hope that you like it." The author is not the reader. The author cannot claim to know what the reader will like.
⚠️ Diversion tactic
Zoey: Given that this FAQ did not answer what the asker is presumably asking for an elaboration, the use of a sales-pitch to promote the project is an act of diversion, an indoctrination technique.

AI has been improving medical diagnosis for decades, starting with rule-based systems like MYCIN in the 1970s and evolving into deep learning models that now outperform doctors in areas like radiology, dermatology, and ophthalmology. Today, AI assists in detecting diseases such as cancer and diabetic retinopathy, with growing applications in predicting disease progression and personalized treatment. [1] The_Unusual
